### Description

**EDIT :** I tried with only `.reverse()` and `trackBy` and this still appear, so async/observable isn't the reason. *ngFor can't track by a reversed array

In my template, I am doing an `*ngFor` over an `Observable<Array<Item>>`. I also reverse that array, in order to show first the most recent item. In order to keep track of this items, I use a `trackBy` function

template.html
```
<div *ngFor="let item of (items$ | async)?.reverse() ; trackBy:trackItemId">
  <div>{{item.name}}<div>
</div>
```

component.ts
```
import { Component, OnInit, TrackByFunction } from '@angular/core';
import { Observable } from 'rxjs';

interface Item {
  name: string;
  id: string;
}

@Component({
  selector: 'app-displayer',
  templateUrl: './displayer.component.html',
  styleUrls: ['./displayer.component.css']
})
export class DisplayerComponent implements OnInit {
  items$: Observable<Array<Item>>;
  trackItemId : TrackByFunction<Item> = (i, item) => item.id;

  constructor() { }

  ngOnInit() {
    this.items$ = this.generateItem();
  }

  generateItem(): Observable<Array<Item>>{
    const items = new Array<Item>();
    const itemName = 'my Item';
    const itemId = 'id-';
    let counter = 0;
    return new Observable((obs) => {
      setInterval(() => {
        counter++;
        items.push({
          name: `${itemName}${counter}`,
          id: `${itemId}${counter}`
        })
        obs.next(items)
      }, 1000)
    })
  }
}
```

This works perfectly in **developer** mode. the item are tracked and appear in order.
But, for some reason, in **production** mode, it fails. items are constantly moved each time a new Item is added to the observable.


## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction
* be care you need to reload every time you change prod/dev mode because it's stackblitz*
https://stackblitz.com/edit/angular-yf9zsk

## Prerequisite
Add in `main.ts`

```
  enableProdMode();
```

